replies.body:
But it wasn't anger and jealousy that they depicted. It was utter depression. Viktor locked himself away from society and demonstrated his genius to show that - even if he could not prove he created Blitzcrank - that he was more than capable of surpassing his previous team-based effort.

He did not lash out;
He did not brag;

When Viktor emerged, he was not Viktor. He was somebody else. He did not call out Stanwick (as far as we know). He did not call for revolution. Indeed; he called for *evolution*, and bade people to see the future that he now envisioned. Whether or not he makes his augments available for charity purposes, they are on the market, he strives towards his obsession. Yes - Viktor is obsessed. He pursues his vision. Would he do it at any cost? Battlecast alternate universe says maybe. But in this universe, he is nothing but an innovator.

An innovator who chose not to pursue justice or revenge. An inventor who created a new step in the evolutionary chain that humanity COULD choose to take. And considering the augmented are 'volunteers', it is evident that he aims to persuade - not to victimise.

Riot thought they were making a villain, maybe. But that's not what they made. They made an identity. And it's bigger than 'Bad Guy".

I get the very real feeling that his story is already underway and mostly fleshed out. But if it is not *yet* complete, this could be a really fun idea. I remember back during the days that we were asking for VIktor's first rework, we put out LOTS of ideas about the direction we felt his kit should follow; along with the best ways to turn his shortcomings to strengths. My particular favourite was "Make sure you auto after using Q, otherwise what's the point in even HAVING the shield?! Soak minion damage and win the trade through sheer persistence!!"

And Solcrushed in all his benevolence GAVE US AN EMPOWERED AUTO! That gesture alone made it all worthwhile! :P

So yeah; it might be worth making the effort! Particularly now that we know *precisely* which Rioter to address.  As an example, maybe...

* We could play through what led him to be the man he is (the sudden epiphany and subsequent obsession with his own self-transformation. The realisation that it was something big. VERY big. With implications such that - should he succeed - humanity might never be the same again. That these "upgrades" could be applied to anybody); 
* We could talk about whether or not he seems to *actually* have removed his emotions, or is merely suppressing them due to his own personal ideals or own insecurities (after all - he sure enjoys lasering a whole bunch for somebody who doesn't feel emotion :P); 
* We could muse upon what lengths he would go to to achieve or reshape his own goals - ie: the Jayce incident. Maybe even a potential justification for what decisions may have been involved in the alternate reality that became the Battlecast universe (I particularly am of the opinion that Battlecast began as a response to the threat of the Void, though Skarner seems out of place. Admittedly, he IS an Alpha model));
* We could even share our thoughts on what that intangible **it** is, that makes VIktor so damn relateable. So seemingly complex, where in actuality, there is very little for us to go on. There's so much *implication* in the things he has simply refrained from doing. The potential is there for him to be quite special.

I think that's the scariest thing, about Viktor changes. The threat of squandered character potential. It would be *so* easy to one-dimension him.
